04786nam a22007215i 9781501724343DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20182001nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017243437 a10.7591/97815017243432doi  a(DE-B1597)515531  a(OCoLC)1091660929  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPS366.A88bG55 2001 7aLIT0060002bisacsh04a818/.508094922211 aGilmore, Leigh, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Limits of Autobiography :bTrauma and Testimony /cLeigh Gilmore. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (176 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION. The Limits of Autobiography -- t1. Represent Yourself -- t2. Bastard Testimony Illegitimacy and Incest in Dorothy Allison’s: Bastard Out of Carolina -- t3. There Will Always Be a Father: Transference and the Auto/biographical Demand in Mikal Gilmore’s Shot in the Heart -- t4. There Will Always Be a Mother: Jamaica Kincaid’s Serial Autobiography -- t5. Without Names: An Anatomy of Absence in Jeanette Winterson’s Written on the Body -- tCONCLUSION. The Knowing Subject and an Alternative Jurisprudence of Trauma -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMemoirs in which trauma takes a major—or the major—role challenge the limits of autobiography. Leigh Gilmore presents a series of "limit-cases"—texts that combine elements of autobiography, fiction, biography, history, and theory while representing trauma and the self—and demonstrates how and why their authors swerve from the formal constraints of autobiography when the representation of trauma coincides with self-representation. Gilmore maintains that conflicting demands on both the self and narrative may prompt formal experimentation by such writers and lead to texts that are not, strictly speaking, autobiography, but are nonetheless deeply engaged with its central concerns.In astute and compelling readings of texts by Michel Foucault, Louis Althusser, Dorothy Allison, Mikal Gilmore, Jamaica Kincaid, and Jeanette Winterson, Gilmore explores how each of them poses the questions, "How have I lived? How will I live?" in relation to the social and psychic forms within which trauma emerges. Challenging the very boundaries of autobiography as well as trauma, these stories are not told in conventional ways: the writers testify to how self-representation and the representation of trauma grow beyond simple causes and effects, exceed their duration in time, and connect to other forms of historical, familial, and personal pain. In their movement from an overtly testimonial form to one that draws on legal as well as literary knowledge, such texts produce an alternative means of confronting kinship, violence, and self-representation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAmerican prose literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAutobiographical fictionxHistory and criticism. 0aAutobiography. 0aEnglish prose literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPhilosophy. 4aPsychology & Psychiatry. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172434340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501724343423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501724343/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deG